            <h2 class="wsite-content-title">9 Tips on how to prevent food waste at home</h2>

            <div class="paragraph" style="color:black;">
              <ol>
                <li><strong>Don't hide your food</strong> (make a corner in the fridge for things you need to use soon
                  or always store new things behind older things when unpacking your shopping)</li>
                <li><strong>Love your leftovers</strong> (challenge yourself to only cook with what is left in the
                  fridge and start packing the rest of dinner in a nice lunch box, ready to bring to your office the
                  next day)</li>
                <li><strong>Make friends and share your food </strong>(bring extra food (before it went bad) to your
                  neighbors, family or working colleagues)</li>
                <li><strong>Use your senses </strong>(look at, smell and taste food before throwing it out because it
                  reached the best before date)</li>
                <li><strong>Check your fridge and storage before going shopping&nbsp;</strong></li>
                <li><strong>Preserve your food </strong>(making jam or freezing some extra soup)&nbsp;</li>
                <li><strong>Store properly&nbsp;</strong>(most fruit lasts much longer if stored in the fridge)</li>
                <li><strong>Shop wisely</strong> (be realistic how much you really need, make and stick to your
                  shopping list, be careful with discounts, that make you buy more, then you need)</li>
                <li><strong>Eat out smart&nbsp;</strong>(order half portions, share a meal, ask for a doggie bag)</li>
              </ol>
            </div>

            <h2 class="wsite-content-title">Tips to reduce food waste at holidays</h2>

            <div class="paragraph">
              <ul>
                <li><strong>Think back of last year</strong>: How many leftovers did you have? What was not perfect?
                  Fine tune.&nbsp;</li>
                <li>Use a <a href="https://www.lovefoodhatewaste.com/portion-planner" target="_blank">portion planer</a>
                  to plan your meal. Especially for big dinners with many people we tend to overcook.&nbsp; Don't worry
                  that your guests will leave your home hungry, there are always cookies to fill up even the biggest
                  eaters.&nbsp;</li>
                <li><strong>Are prepared to deal with leftovers</strong>: Ask guests to bring containers, keep
                  disposable containers like pickle jars, big yogurt containers and ice-cream boxes for the big day to
                  have some containers to give guests, make sure to have some freezing containers, bags at home</li>
              </ul>
